name: HttpRequests
content:
Introduction

In this lesson, we'll explore HTTP requests, which are a fundamental concept in web development. They are the means by which clients (such as web browsers) communicate with servers to retrieve or send data over the internet.

Exploring the Relationship Between API and HTTP Requests

What's the relation between API and HTTP requests?

In our analogy, envision theAPIas thewaiterin a restaurant, andHTTP requestsas theordersplaced by customers (clients). Just as customers interact with thewaiter(API) to convey their requests, web clients interact with the API by making HTTP requests.

In the realm of web development, an API exposes a single endpoint, while it is the user's role to provide the specific requests that the API can accommodate. As developers, we design and implement these processes that the API can handle effectively.

Understanding HTTP Methods

HTTP methods are the means by which a web server communicates with a client. There are five common methods that can be used to communicate with a web server:

  • GET:

    The GET method is used to retrieve data from a web server. It is primarily used for reading information and should not have side effects on the server. For example, fetching a webpage or requesting data from an API. The GET method is optimized such that any same GET request should always provide the same results. The GET request should have no body, and any details should be in the URL.

    Key Characteristics of GET:
    • Read-Only:GET is a read-only method that is used for retrieving data without altering the server's state. It's ideal for fetching information.
    • Idempotent:GET requests are idempotent, meaning that multiple identical GET requests will produce the same result. This property makes GET suitable for caching.
    • No Request Body:Unlike some other methods, GET requests do not include a request body. Instead, the details are typically included in the URL as query parameters.
  • POST:

    POST is used to send data to a web server to create a new resource. It can be used for submitting forms, uploading files, or making any request that results in the creation of a new entity on the server.

    Key Characteristics of POST:
    • Create Resource:POST requests are used to create new resources on the server. They are typically associated with actions that modify server data, such as adding a new user to a database.
    • Non-Idempotent:Unlike GET requests, POST requests are not idempotent. Sending the same POST request multiple times may result in the creation of multiple resources.
    • Request Body:POST requests include a request body where data to be added or modified is sent. This data can be in various formats, including JSON, form data, or file uploads.
  • PUT:

    PUT is used to update an existing resource on the web server. It replaces the entire resource with the new data provided in the request. It's suitable for updating or replacing an entire resource.

  • PATCH:

    PATCH is used to apply partial modifications to a resource. It's often used when you want to update specific fields of an existing resource without affecting the rest of it.

  • DELETE:

    DELETE is used to request the removal of a resource from the web server. It is used to delete the specified resource, and it should only perform that action.

Brain Teaser

Situation: You are creating a login page, and you want to get user data from the server using their username and password.

Question: What kind of HTTP method should you use?

Answer

POST

Expand Your Knowledge: As we can see above, GET requests are used to reading data on the server, during login, we only read the data of the account owner, right? but why should we use POST instead of GET?

name: API
content:
Introduction

APIs are a key part of any web application. In this lesson, you'll learn about the basics of APIs and how it relates to express js.

What is an API?

An API , short for Application Programming Interface , is like a waiter in a restaurant. It acts as a middleman between a customer (user) and the kitchen (application) . The customer places an order with the waiter , who then communicates the order to the chef , ensuring that the customer gets the desired dish . Similarly, in software, an API allows one application to request and exchange data with another, facilitating seamless communication.

Understanding API Endpoints

API endpoints are like the entry points or addresses of an API. They serve as the specific URLs that users can use to interact with the API's functionality. You can think of API endpoints as similar to items on a menu.

In the web, an API endpoint is typically what follows after the domain. Take a look at the example below:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ

The domain is www.youtube.com, and in this example, the API endpoint is /watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ.
